  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The COVID-19 Open Research Dataset (CORD-19) has been accessed 16,652 times and viewed 20,217 times, indicating active utilization by researchers and practitioners. Despite its critical relevance, it has received four citations to date, suggesting initial acknowledgment within the scholarly community.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Launched in 2020, the COVID-19 Open Research Dataset (CORD-19), authored by a team from the Allen Institute, compiles extensive research on the pandemic, focusing on crucial topics such as COVID-19, SARS-CoV-2, and virology. With an open access designation, CORD-19 facilitates knowledge sharing in an urgent area of global health.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Usage metrics reflect significant engagement, evidenced by 16,652 downloads and 20,217 views, demonstrating the dataset's importance to ongoing research efforts. However, its citation impact remains modest with only four citations recorded, indicating that while the dataset has been pivotal in initial research phases, its influence on subsequent studies and publications is still in early stages.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset has seen a proven reuse in various contexts, with four documented cases of downstream usage, including a notable review and three preprints, underlining its role in fostering further investigation on related themes. Yet, there are no online mentions or broader community discourse captured, which suggests a potential gap in outreach or visibility given the critical nature of the content.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In summary, while the dataset has been instrumental in providing foundational data during a pivotal time, its relatively low citation count highlights the ongoing challenge of transforming early engagement into long-term scholarly impact. Continued monitoring of its usage and integration into broader research narratives will be essential as the academic community navigates the complexities of COVID-19 and its implications.</p>",
